<dl id="n38018f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38018f">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38018f"> 18(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> stoolball <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n38018f"><li>FW 129.29 </li><li><a href="../../flex/fa/lexfa.htm#n38018f">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/fa/l39fa.htm#n38018f">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n38018f">MS BL 47475-271</ms> </li><li>JJA 47:264 <a name="fad6y" href="../../FF/fdra/fda.htm#fad6y">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/fa/fad6.htm#n38018f">Draft: I.6&sect;1.6</a>+</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><b>Oldest Game in Britain / Stoolball Played at Arundel / Duke&apos;s Big Innings / From Our Special Correspondent</b> At the invitation of the Duke of Norfolk the &ldquo;Men of Sussex,&rdquo; on the occasion of their annual summer outing on Saturday, spent the day at Arundel Castle. The morning was devoted to an inspection of the ancient stronghold, and in the afternoon <mark>stoolball</mark>, which is said to be the oldest game in England, was played on the beautiful tilting ground. <br>Except for the wickets, bats, and ball, the game closely resembles cricket. It is believed that when the game was originally played in Sussex milkmaids&apos; stools were used as wickets. <small> <a name="DT19may30" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#DT19may30"><cite title="source">Daily Telegraph</cite></a> (19 May 1930) 14/2</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: The game was reported in several British papers, but it was not possible to determine which was Joyce&apos;s source: this version was chosen as the clearest account of the game itself. Stool-ball: an old country game somewhat resembling cricket, played chiefly by young women, or, as an Easter game, between men and women for a &lsquo;tansy&rsquo; as the stake. The &lsquo;stool&rsquo; was the wicket. Element appears also at <a name="sd1043i" href="sd1all.htm#sd1043i">SD1 (VI.A):043(i)</a>. </mm> </dd></dl>
